The stock
column2: which recently ended development of an experimental therapy for Covid-19
column3: rallied to close 39% higher on Monday after a poster on Reddit’s WallStreetBets forum called it “the most undervalued stock in the market” while another said a brewing BioWar was “about sticking it to the shorts in a massive way. ”​Biotechs with little to no revenue have long been the focus of short bets on Wall Street and could emerge as a new focal point for small-time investors railing against elite hedge funds.  But the battleground is an already crowded arena with hedge funds positioned on both sides. Indeed
column4: BioCryst is a short target with about 17% of float
column7: according to financial analytics firm S3 Partners.  But it’s also a hedge fund pick held by the likes of Citadel
column8: the well-known biotech outfit Baker Bros.  Advisors LP
column9: and activist investor Alex Denner’s Sarissa Capital Management. Before Monday’s rally
column10: shares of BioCryst had already shrugged off the scuttling of a Covid-19 trial supported by the National Institutes of Health.  The company is expected to generate less than $31 million in revenue for all of 2020. Novavax Inc.
column12: has also garnered interest across chat forums
column13: which could benefit funds like RA Capital Management and Perceptive Advisors
column14: which hold stakes in the company.  The stock has more than doubled in the past few trading days
column15: albeit on late-stage positive results for its Covid-19 vaccine candidate.  The short position on Novavax stands at $1. 5 billion
column16: according to S3. Throughout the pandemic
column17: biotechs racing to find the next Covid-19 treatment or vaccine have captured the imagination of retail investors.  Dynavax Technologies Corp.  added another $436 million in market value on Monday on news it had both initiated a mid-stage Covid vaccine study with one partner and that the U. K.  had exercised an option to order more inoculations from another Dynavax partner using the company’s adjuvant. Inovio Pharmaceuticals Inc.  also soared Monday after Twitter users jumped on a filing over BlackRock Inc. ’s stake in the company.  One tweet said BlackRock had doubled its position
column18: although Bloomberg data show the stake is virtually unchanged. Meanwhile
column19: the motivations behind Monday’s 131% rally in Healthier Choices Management Corp.  powered by Reddit was unclear as Twitter users said it was an opportunity to send hedge funds “on the run. ” Short interest in the sub-penny stock
column20: which makes vaping products and operates health food stores in Florida

column3: who grilled him extensively on recent events.  What Happened: Tenev said it had been a “surreal” week for him
column4: in a reference to the Reddit investor-led short squeeze rally in the shares of Gamestop Corp (NYSE: GME)
column7: Blackberry Ltd (NYSE: BB) and others.  The brokerage head referred to these stocks as “meme stocks” throughout the broadcast where he appeared to clarify the events of the tumultuous week — when purchase of such stocks was restricted on the popular trading app.  Tenev said the app experienced “unprecedented volume” and “load on the system. ” He pointed out that the net buys increased exponentially.  Robinhood was among the top apps on Apple Inc (NASDAQ: AAPL) and Alphabet Inc’s (NASDAQ: GOOGL) (NASDAQ: GOOG) respective app stores as of last week
column8: Tenev noted.  Detailing the sequence of events that led to the suspension of buying in the Reddit-fueled stocks
column9: he said Robinhood received a demand for $3 billion from the National Securities Clearing Corporation in the wee hours of Thursday.  NSCC provides clearing
column12: and central counterparty services.  The executive explained that Robinhood had to put up money for the NSCC based volatility and the concentration of securities but the formula behind the demand was not fully known to him.  Why It Matters: The NSCC is not a government agency but is rather controlled by a consortium
column13: as per Tenev.  The executive said that on Monday’s opening

column1: 2021-02-01 00:13:02#world#I didn’t believe the virus was real
column2: Covid-19 patients told nurse#https://www.msn.com/en-gb/news/world/i-didnt-believe-the-virus-was-real-covid-19-patients-told-nurse/vi-BB1dgGsz#https://www.msn.com/en-gb/news/world/i-didnt-believe-the-virus-was-real-covid-19-patients-told-nurse/vi-BB1dgGsz#en#0.0#www.msn.com#A senior nurse in a coronavirus ward has said patients told her they did not believe the virus was real.  Senior charge nurse Rosario Walshe leads the team at Ward A31 at Forth Valley Royal Hospital in Larbert in the Falkirk Council area and said there has been a “huge spike” in cases recently.  The PA news agency was given access to the 32-bed Covid-19 ward where every bed was taken as hospital referrals have doubled since the first wave.  Ms Walshe believes a combination of family gatherings at Christmas
column3: people ignoring guidelines and the new rapidly-spreading variant is behind the rise.  “I’ve had patients say to me
column4: ‘I wish I had listened
column5: I didn’t listen.  I didn’t really believe it was real
column6: ’ so that was quite an eye opener
column7: ” she said.  “The last few weeks have been extremely busy and challenging.  It’s definitely different to the first wave.  “We’ve seen a lot more admissions with Covid-related symptoms – we’ve seen lots of groups of family members admitted with Covid
column8: a lot of young people
column9: which you didn’t see so much in the first wave.  “We’ve had some extremely sick people.  Patients discussed with ITU (intensive treatment unit)
column10: some transferred to ITU.  It’s definitely been a lot more challenging. ” “The reasons for it getting worse I think I can only assume that people weren’t following the guidelines.  “We’ve seen a huge spike in our cases
column11: so I think we can all assume that family get-togethers at Christmas are one of the reasons our cases have gone up so much.  “It does annoy me slightly
column12: lots of staff members are adhering to the policies and guidelines
column13: trying really hard to socially distance and then you’ve got people who refuse to believe this is real.  We still have the element of people that don’t believe. ”#https://www.msn.com/en-gb/news/world/i-didnt-believe-the-virus-was-real-covid-19-patients-told-nurse/vi-BB1dgGsz#NlcAIQUQy

column2: last week
column3: Facebook CEO Mark Zuckerberg reached out to lawmakers in Australia to discuss a planned law that would result in internet giants like Facebook (FB) and Google (GOOGL) paying media outlets for content used on their sites.  However
column4: Mark Zuckerberg failed to persuade lawmakers to change the policy
column5: according to Reuters.  The report also says that Australian Treasurer Josh Frydenberg told Australian Broadcasting Corp
column7: Mark Zuckerberg didn’t convince me to back down if that’s what you’re asking. ” According to the proposed law
column8: news media outlets can negotiate collectively or individually
column9: over content that drives traffic to Facebook and Google’s websites.  If these parties fail to reach an agreement
column10: an arbitrator appointed by the Australian Government will set the fees for both parties.  In view of this proposed law
column12: Facebook had said that it will stop news sharing if the Australian government proceeds while Google threatened to withdraw its search engine from the country.  Companies like Facebook are opposing this law as it would mean an increase in compliance costs and could also put a dent in its advertising revenues as the proposed law also states that companies will have to share their consumer data from such news content.  Advertising is a major source of revenue for Facebook.  (See Facebook stock analysis on TipRanks) In the fourth quarter
column13: Facebook reported advertising revenues of $27. 2 billion
column14: up by 31% year-on-year.  The advertising business made up about 96. 8% of total revenues in 4Q for the company.  Mark Zuckerberg also warned of the timing of “platform changes
column16: as well as the evolving regulatory landscape
column17: ” during Facebook’s 4Q results.  William Blair analyst Ralph Schackart reiterated a Buy rating on the stock on Jan.  28.  Commenting on the company’s 4Q results
column20: Facebook will lap a period of growth that was negatively affected by reduced advertising demand during the early stages of the pandemic.  Thus
column21: year-over year growth rates in total revenue are expected to remain stable or modestly accelerate sequentially during the first and second quarters of 2021. ” “In the second half of the year
column22: Facebook will lap periods of increasingly strong growth
column23: which is expected to put significant pressure on year-over-year growth rates
column24: ” Schackart added.  The rest of the Street is bullish about the stock with a Strong Buy consensus rating.  That’s based on 35 analysts recommending a Buy

column1: 2021-01-31 06:54:49#entertainment#‘Glitch in the Matrix’ Film Review: Trippy Documentary Questions the Nature of Reality#https://www.yahoo.com/entertainment/glitch-matrix-film-review-trippy-065449379.html#https://s.yimg.com/uu/api/res/1.2/C.AZd9jQODadcTHRBiSFlQ--~B/aD00MDA7dz02MTg7YXBwaWQ9eXRhY2h5b24-/https://media.zenfs.com/en/thewrap.com/b19ad26596b0923516ae98fcdae1fd7e#en#0.0#www.yahoo.com#Director Rodney Ascher’s specialty is obsession
column2: but his approach succeeds as compassion.  After giving voice to people consumed by “The Shining” (“Room 237”)
column3: ventriloquist dummies (“The Wooden Boy”) and sleep paralysis (“The Nightmare”)
column4: he’s shifted his attention to simulation theory with “Glitch in the Matrix
column5: ” premiering at Sundance just before it goes into wider release.  A subject tailor-made for college
column7: simulation theory questions human determination by positing that we are merely avatars
column8: and that some greater force — an external gamer
column9: if you will — is our master manipulator.  Much of this concept comes directly from sci-fi writer Philip K.  Dick
column10: who is copiously represented throughout “Glitch. ” Ascher makes much use of a recorded 1977 event in which Dick presents these ideas with utmost sincerity
column11: even while admitting that “I may be talking about something which does not exist.  Therefore
column12: I am free to say everything and nothing. ” Also Read: Rodney Ascher's 'A Glitch in the Matrix' Acquired by Magnolia Ahead of Sundance Premiere Ascher takes a similar approach
column13: wandering through as many musings that’ll elicit a “What?” as much as a “Whoa. ” Speaking of which
column14: it may not surprise anyone to learn that Keanu Reeves is the icon of this ideology
column15: just as “The Matrix” trilogy is its Bible.  He doesn’t
column17: consider these films to be anything beyond fantasy
column18: but there are lots of interviews with adherents like Brother Læo Mystwood
column19: who came to his beliefs after noticing a pattern of synchronicities (some viewers might call them coincidences) in his life.  Ascher transforms many of his subjects into Fortnight-style characters themselves
column20: an approach that feels alternately inspired and unfortunate.  On the one hand
column21: using 3D motion-capture animation to turn people who believe they may be avatars into actual avatars offers a cheeky
column23: bit of visual parallelism.  And since we never see their true appearance
column24: they’re afforded privacy while sharing their controversial views.  Also Read: Amazon's 'Electric Dreams' Hints at What Might Have Happened to Real-Life Philip K.  Dick Android That said
column25: neither anonymity nor resemblance to a competitor on “The Masked Singer” does much to boost anyone’s credibility.  In truth
column26: many of them seem to be vulnerable individuals searching for comfort
column27: rather than philosophers or theorists.  But just as we realize this
column28: Ascher shifts into an examination of the reasons simulation and false identity theories have proven popular among adherents.  We’re reminded of the movies that paved the way for cultural infiltration
column33: there is the franchise that gives this film its name.  In the most troubling
column36: we hear Joshua Cooke describe in detail the events that led to the murder of his parents
column37: while the camera brings us there virtually though animated photogrammetry.  Also Read: Lilly Wachowski Tells Elon Musk and Ivanka Trump 'F-- Both of You' After They Quote 'The Matrix' Cooke connected with Reeves’ character Neo to such a degree that his lawyers prepped a “Matrix Defense
column38: ” an insanity plea based on the idea that he deeply believed in a parallel reality.  Ascher leaves us pondering the costs of dissociation
column39: but also its seductive appeal.  Is it really that outlandish to look around occasionally
column40: and wonder at the surreality of it all? “Glitch in the Matrix” opens in select theaters and on-demand Feb.  5.  ﻿ Read original story ‘Glitch in the Matrix’ Film Review: Trippy Documentary Questions the Nature of Reality At TheWrap#https://www.yahoo.com/entertainment/glitch-matrix-film-review-trippy-065449379.html#vA5q49xxi
